  "opinion": "As a woman in her 50s who works part-time as a cleaner in Lecce, I’ve seen how stereotype threat plays out in STEM fields firsthand. Growing up in a family where my father had a vocational diploma and my mother a master’s degree, I learned early that being a woman in technical fields wasn’t something I should expect to excel at without extra effort. Back in the day, when I was in school, teachers would often say things like, 'You’re too soft for math,' or 'Girls don’t do engineering.' These comments, though seemingly minor, planted seeds of doubt that stuck with me. Now, as someone who reads novels and enjoys rock climbing—a hobby that requires focus and physical strength—I know that confidence comes from within. But in STEM, where people often assume women are less capable, it’s a real struggle. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory; it’s a daily reality for many women who try to break into these fields. I think we absolutely should address it. In my community, where I’ve seen friends struggle with math because they were told they weren’t ‘the type’ for it, I believe the solution lies in small, consistent changes. Schools should have more role models who are women in STEM, and workplaces should create environments where everyone feels safe to ask questions without fear of judgment. For example, in my city, Lecce, there are few women in tech jobs, so it’s important to encourage girls to pursue STEM early on, even if they’re not sure they’ll succeed. But the key is to be patient and supportive, not to push them too hard. I’ve learned through my own anxiety that it’s better to build confidence slowly, step by step. If we don’t address stereotype threat, more women will stay out of STEM, and we’ll lose out on talent and diversity. It’s not just about fixing the system—it’s about creating a world where everyone feels they belong.",
